@palango what type of node are you connecting to?

Reason I ask is that web3 doesn't actually implement any logic related to gathering the appropriate events.  It merely delegates these calls to the node that it's connected to.  So, the error you're seeing is likely not a web3.py one, but something wrong with the node you are connecting to.

Also, there *could* be a race condition at play.  I don't know, but you might see if you get different results if you put a `time.sleep()` between the creation of the filter, and the calls to get the events.

